 exchange between material elements.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsection
The ADER-WENO Method
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:The-ADER-WENO-Method"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The GPR model, being non-conservative, with stiff source terms, represents
 a particularly challenging set of PDEs.
 In this study they are solved by an ADER-WENO method.
 First, the cell-wise constant state variable data from the current time
 step is reconstructed using high-order spatial polynomials according to
 the WENO method.
 This reconstruction is then extended to a reconstruction in both space
 and time for each individual cell in the domain, using the Discontinuous
 Galerkin method.
 A finite volume solver is then used to couple neighbouring cells and produce
 the cell-wise constant data at the next time step.
 In this study, all simulations were performed in 1D.
 The methods presented here are easily extensible to higher dimensions,
 however.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Although this process has been demonstrated to be effective in solving the
 GPR system 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dumbser2015,Boscheri2016"

\end_inset

, it was originally designed for problems involving moving meshes, and is
 probably more involved than necessary to perform the simulations in this
 study.
 The DG step in particular is relatively computationally taxing.
 The purpose of this study, however, was not to investigate more efficient
 solution methods for this particular system (see Sverdrup 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "knutsverdrup2016"

\end_inset

 for the latest work on this problem).
 It was therefore decided that this procedure would be used, being the only
 confirmed method of solution publicly available.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
The WENO Reconstruction
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
First introduced by Liu et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Liu1994"

\end_inset

 and developed by Jiang and Shu 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jiang1996"

\end_inset

, WENO methods are used to produce high order polynomial approximations
 to piece-wise constant data.
 In this study, the modified method of Dumbser et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dumbser2013"

\end_inset

 is used.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Consider the domain 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,L\right]$
\end_inset

.
 Take 
\begin_inset Formula $K,N\in\mathbb{N}$
\end_inset

.
 Take the set of grid points 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}=\frac{i\cdot L}{K}$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $i=0,\ldots,K$
\end_inset

 and let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta x=\frac{L}{K}$
\end_inset

.
 Denote cell 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[x_{i},x_{i+1}\right]$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset

.
 Given cell-wise constant data 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,L\right]$
\end_inset

, an order 
\begin_inset Formula $N+1$
\end_inset

 accurate polynomial reconstruction of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset

 will be performed.
 Define the scaled space variable:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\chi^{i}=\frac{1}{\Delta x}\left(x-x_{i}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Denoting the Gauss-Legendre abscissae on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \chi_{0},\ldots,\chi_{N}\right\} $
\end_inset

, define the nodal basis of order 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

: the Lagrange interpolating polynomials 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \psi_{0},\ldots,\psi_{N}\right\} $
\end_inset

 with the following property:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\psi_{i}\left(\chi_{j}\right)=\delta_{ij}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is even, take the stencils:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
S_{1} & =\left\{ C_{i-\frac{N}{2}},\ldots,C_{i+\frac{N}{2}}\right\} \\
S_{2} & =\left\{ C_{i-N},\ldots,C_{i}\right\} \\
S_{3} & =\left\{ C_{i},\ldots,C_{i+N}\right\} 
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
If 
\begin_inset Formula $N$
\end_inset

 is odd, take the stencils:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\begin{cases}
S_{1} & =\left\{ C_{i-\left\lfloor \frac{N}{2}\right\rfloor },\ldots,C_{i+\left\lceil \frac{N}{2}\right\rceil }\right\} \\
S_{2} & =\left\{ C_{i-\left\lceil \frac{N}{2}\right\rceil },\ldots,C_{i+\left\lfloor \frac{N}{2}\right\rfloor }\right\} \\
S_{3} & =\left\{ C_{i-N},\ldots,C_{i}\right\} \\
S_{4} & =\left\{ C_{i},\ldots,C_{i+N}\right\} 
\end{cases}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The data is reconstructed on 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{j}$
\end_inset

 as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\sum_{p}\psi_{p}\left(\chi^{i}\left(x\right)\right)\hat{w}_{p}^{ij}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where the 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{w}_{p}^{ij}$
\end_inset

 are solutions to the following linear system:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{1}{\Delta x}\int_{x_{k}}^{x_{k+1}}\psi_{p}\left(\chi^{k}\left(x\right)\right)\hat{w}_{p}^{ij}dx=u_{k}\qquad\forall C_{k}\in S_{j}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $u_{k}$
\end_inset

 is the value of 
\begin_inset Formula $u$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{k}$
\end_inset

.
 Define the oscillation indicator matrix:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\Sigma_{mn}=\sum_{\alpha=1}^{N}\int_{0}^{1}\psi_{m}^{\left(\alpha\right)}\psi_{n}^{\left(\alpha\right)}d\chi
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
and the oscillation indicator for each stencil:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
o_{j}=\Sigma_{mn}\hat{w}_{m}^{ij}\hat{w}_{n}^{ij}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The full reconstruction in 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset

 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
w_{i}\left(x\right)=\sum_{p}\psi_{p}\left(\chi^{i}\left(x\right)\right)\hat{w}_{p}^{i}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{w}_{p}^{i}=\omega_{j}\hat{w}_{p}^{ij}$
\end_inset

 is the weighted coefficient of the 
\begin_inset Formula $p$
\end_inset

th basis function, with weights:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\omega_{j}=\frac{\tilde{\omega}_{j}}{\sum_{k}\tilde{\omega}_{k}}\qquad\tilde{\omega}_{j}=\frac{\zeta_{j}}{\left(o_{s}+\varepsilon\right)^{r}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In this study, 
\begin_inset Formula $r=8$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\varepsilon=10^{-14}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{j}=10^{5}$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{j}$
\end_inset

 is a central stencil, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\zeta_{j}=1$
\end_inset

 if 
\begin_inset Formula $S_{j}$
\end_inset

 is a side stencil, as in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dumbser2014"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
The Discontinuous Galerkin Predictor 
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:The Discontinuous Galerkin Predictor"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Take a non-conservative, hyperbolic system of the form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{Q}}{\partial t}+\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)}{\partial x}+B\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)\cdot\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{Q}}{\partial x}=\boldsymbol{S}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)\label{eq:NonConservativeSystem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q}$
\end_inset

 is the vector of conserved variables, 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{F}$
\end_inset

 is the conservative nonlinear flux, 
\begin_inset Formula $B$
\end_inset

 is the block matrix corresponding to the purely non-conservative component
 of the system, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{S}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)$
\end_inset

 is the algebraic source vector.
 Defining 
\begin_inset Formula $M=\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{F}}{\partial\boldsymbol{Q}}+B$
\end_inset

 this becomes:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{Q}}{\partial t}+M\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)\cdot\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{Q}}{\partial x}=\boldsymbol{S}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)\label{eq:NonConservativeSystem2}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Take the grid for the previous section, and time steps 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{0}<t_{1}<\ldots$
\end_inset

 while defining 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta t_{n}=t_{n+1}-t_{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Combining the techniques presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dumbser2009,Dumbser2014"

\end_inset

, the Discontinuous Galerkin method produces at each time step 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset

 a local polynomial approximation to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q}$
\end_inset

 on each space-time cell 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}\times\left[t_{n},t_{n+1}\right]$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Define the scaled time variable:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tau^{n}=\frac{1}{\Delta t_{n}}\left(t-t_{n}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using these variables gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{Q}}{\partial\tau^{n}}+\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{F^{*}}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)}{\partial\chi^{i}}+B^{*}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)\cdot\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{Q}}{\partial\chi^{i}}=\boldsymbol{S^{*}}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)\label{eq:NonDimensionalNonConservativeSystem}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{F^{*}}=\frac{\Delta t_{n}}{\Delta x}\boldsymbol{F}\qquad B^{*}=\frac{\Delta t_{n}}{\Delta x}B\qquad\boldsymbol{S^{*}}=\Delta t_{n}\boldsymbol{S}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The non-dimensionalisation notation and spacetime cell indexing notation
 will be dropped for simplicity in what follows.
 Using the same nodal basis as in the previous section, define the set of
 spatio-temporal basis functions:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left\{ \theta_{k}\left(\chi,\tau\right)=\psi_{p}\left(\chi\right)\psi_{s}\left(\tau\right):0\leq p,s\leq N\right\} 
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The 
\shape italic
nodal basis representation
\shape default
 is the following set of approximations:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\boldsymbol{Q} & \approx\boldsymbol{q_{h}}=\theta_{\beta}\boldsymbol{q_{\beta}}\\
\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right) & \approx\theta_{\beta}\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{q_{\beta}}\right)\\
B\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)\cdot\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{Q}}{\partial\chi} & \approx\theta_{\beta}B\left(\boldsymbol{q_{\beta}}\right)\cdot\left(\frac{\partial\theta_{\gamma}\left(\chi_{\beta},\tau_{\beta}\right)}{\partial\chi}\boldsymbol{q_{\gamma}}\right)\\
\boldsymbol{S}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right) & \approx\theta_{\beta}\boldsymbol{S}\left(\boldsymbol{q_{\beta}}\right)
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\left(\chi_{\beta},\tau_{\beta}\right)$
\end_inset

 are the coordinates of the Legendre node corresponding to basis function
 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{\beta}$
\end_inset

.
 Define the integral operators:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left[f,g\right]^{\tau} & =\int_{0}^{1}f\left(\chi,\tau\right)g\left(\chi,\tau\right)d\chi\\
\left\langle f,g\right\rangle  & =\int_{0}^{1}\int_{0}^{1}f\left(\chi,\tau\right)g\left(\chi,\tau\right)d\chi d\tau
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using the nodal basis representation, multiplying 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:NonDimensionalNonConservativeSystem"

\end_inset

 by test function 
\begin_inset Formula $\theta_{\alpha}$
\end_inset

 and integrating over space and time gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left\langle \theta_{\alpha},\frac{\partial\theta_{\beta}}{\partial\tau}\right\rangle \boldsymbol{q_{\beta}} & =-\left\langle \theta_{\alpha},\frac{\partial\theta_{\beta}}{\partial\chi}\right\rangle \boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{q_{\beta}}\right)\\
 & \quad+\left\langle \theta_{\alpha},\theta_{\beta}\right\rangle \left(\boldsymbol{S}\left(\boldsymbol{q_{\beta}}\right)-B\left(\boldsymbol{q_{\beta}}\right)\cdot\left(\frac{\partial\theta_{\gamma}\left(\chi_{\beta},\tau_{\beta}\right)}{\partial\chi}\boldsymbol{q_{\gamma}}\right)\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Integrating by parts in time gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\left(\left[\theta_{\alpha},\theta_{\beta}\right]^{1}-\left\langle \frac{\partial\theta_{\alpha}}{\partial\tau},\theta_{\beta}\right\rangle \right)\boldsymbol{q_{\beta}} & =\left[\theta_{\alpha},\boldsymbol{w}\right]^{0}-\left\langle \theta_{\alpha},\frac{\partial\theta_{\beta}}{\partial\chi}\right\rangle \boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{q_{\beta}}\right)\\
 & \quad+\left\langle \theta_{\alpha},\theta_{\beta}\right\rangle \left(\boldsymbol{S}\left(\boldsymbol{q_{\beta}}\right)-B\left(\boldsymbol{q_{\beta}}\right)\cdot\left(\frac{\partial\theta_{\gamma}\left(\chi_{\beta},\tau_{\beta}\right)}{\partial\chi}\boldsymbol{q_{\gamma}}\right)\right)\nonumber 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{w}=\boldsymbol{w_{\gamma}}\psi_{\gamma}$
\end_inset

 is the reconstruction obtained at the start of the time step with the WENO
 method.
 Define the following notation:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
U_{\alpha\beta} & =\left[\theta_{\alpha},\theta_{\beta}\right]^{1}-\left\langle \frac{\partial\theta_{\alpha}}{\partial\tau},\theta_{\beta}\right\rangle \\
V_{\alpha\beta} & =\left\langle \theta_{\alpha},\frac{\partial\theta_{\beta}}{\partial\chi}\right\rangle \\
W_{\alpha\gamma} & =\left[\theta_{\alpha},\psi_{\gamma}\right]^{0}\\
Z_{\alpha\beta} & =\left\langle \theta_{\alpha},\theta_{\beta}\right\rangle 
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Thus:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
U_{\alpha\beta}\boldsymbol{q_{\beta}}=W_{\alpha\gamma}\boldsymbol{w_{\gamma}}-V_{\alpha\beta}\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{q_{\beta}}\right)+Z_{\alpha\beta}\left(\boldsymbol{S}\left(\boldsymbol{q_{\beta}}\right)-B\left(\boldsymbol{q_{\beta}}\right)\cdot\left(\frac{\partial\theta_{\gamma}\left(\chi_{\beta},\tau_{\beta}\right)}{\partial\chi}\boldsymbol{q_{\gamma}}\right)\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
This nonlinear system in 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{q_{\beta}}$
\end_inset

 is solved by a Newton method.
 The source terms must be solved implicitly if they are stiff.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection*
The Predictor Initial Guess
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let the initial guess for the nonlinear system of the DG predictor be 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{q_{h}^{0}}=\theta_{k}\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{k}}$
\end_inset

.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dumbser2010"

\end_inset

 this is taken to be the WENO reconstruction, i.e.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{q_{h}^{0}}\left(\chi,\tau\right)=\boldsymbol{w}\left(\chi\right)$
\end_inset

 for 
\begin_inset Formula $\tau\in\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

.
 In 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Hidalgo2011"

\end_inset

, a more sophisticated initial guess is used for systems of the form 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:NonConservativeSystem"

\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $B=0$
\end_inset

.
 Denote the Gauss-Legendre abscissae on 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,1\right]$
\end_inset

 by 
\begin_inset Formula $\left\{ \tau_{0},\ldots,\tau_{N}\right\} $
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\Delta\tau_{j}=\tau_{j+1}-\tau_{j}$
\end_inset

.
 Letting 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{q_{h}^{0}}=\psi_{i}\left(\chi\right)\psi_{j}\left(\tau\right)\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{ij}}$
\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{i,j+1}} & =\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{ij}}-\Delta\tau_{j}\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{ij}}\right)}{\partial x}+\frac{\Delta\tau_{j}}{2}\left(\boldsymbol{S}\left(\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{i,j+1}}\right)+\boldsymbol{S}\left(\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{ij}}\right)\right)\\
\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{i0}} & =\boldsymbol{w_{i}}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
An explicit second order Taylor method is used to solve the flux term, combined
 with a second order Crank–Nicholson scheme for the stiff source term.
 In this study, this method was adapted to deal with the non-conservative
 terms:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{i,j+1}} & =\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{ij}}-\Delta\tau_{j}M\left(\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{ij}}\right)\cdot\left(\frac{\partial\psi_{k}}{\partial\chi}\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{kj}}\right)+\frac{\Delta\tau_{j}}{2}\left(\boldsymbol{S}\left(\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{i,j+1}}\right)+\boldsymbol{S}\left(\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{ij}}\right)\right)\\
\boldsymbol{\hat{q}_{i0}} & =\boldsymbol{w_{i}}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

 is given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:NonConservativeSystem2"

\end_inset

.
 The Taylor method for the flux term is no longer necessary.
 The system was solved by a Newton method to deal with the stiff source
 term.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It was found that the more sophisticated initial guess would reduce overall
 computation times on some problems, owing to a faster convergence of the
 DG calculation.
 On other problems, the total computation time would increase, owing to
 the added cost of calculating the initial guess.
 See 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dumbser2008,Dumbser2008a,Dumbser2009a"

\end_inset

 for other choices for the initial guess.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
The Finite Volume Scheme
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Following the formulation of 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dumbser2014"

\end_inset

, integrating 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:NonConservativeSystem"

\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[t_{n},t_{n+1}\right]\times C_{i}$
\end_inset

 gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{Q_{i}^{n+1}}=\boldsymbol{Q_{i}^{n}}+\Delta t_{n}\left(\boldsymbol{S_{i}^{n}}-\boldsymbol{P_{i}^{n}}\right)-\frac{\Delta t_{n}}{\Delta x}\left(\boldsymbol{D_{i+1}^{n}}-\boldsymbol{D_{i}^{n}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\boldsymbol{Q_{i}^{n}} & =\frac{1}{\Delta x}\int_{x_{i}}^{x_{i+1}}\boldsymbol{Q}\left(x,t_{n}\right)dx\\
\boldsymbol{S_{i}^{n}} & =\frac{1}{\Delta t_{n}\Delta x}\int_{t_{n}}^{t_{n+1}}\int_{x_{i}}^{x_{i+1}}\boldsymbol{S}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)dxdt\\
\boldsymbol{P_{i}^{n}} & =\frac{1}{\Delta t_{n}\Delta x}\int_{t_{n}}^{t_{n+1}}\int_{x_{i}}^{x_{i+1}}B\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)\cdot\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{Q}}{\partial x}dxdt\\
\boldsymbol{D_{i}^{n}} & =\frac{1}{\Delta t_{n}}\int_{t_{n}}^{t_{n+1}}\boldsymbol{\mathcal{D}}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}\left(x_{i},t\right),\boldsymbol{Q^{+}}\left(x_{i},t\right)\right)dt
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q^{-},Q^{+}}$
\end_inset

 are the left and right extrapolated states at the 
\begin_inset Formula $x_{i}$
\end_inset

 boundary.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{S_{i}^{n}},\boldsymbol{P_{i}^{n}},\boldsymbol{D_{i}^{n}}$
\end_inset

 are calculated using an 
\begin_inset Formula $N+1$
\end_inset

-point Gauss-Legendre quadrature, replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q}$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{q_{h}}$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $M$
\end_inset

, as defined in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:The Discontinuous Galerkin Predictor"

\end_inset

, is a diagonalisable matrix with decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula $M=R\Lambda R^{-1}$
\end_inset

 where the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $R$
\end_inset

 are the right eigenvectors and 
\begin_inset Formula $\Lambda$
\end_inset

 is the diagonal matrix of eigenvalues.
 Define the following matrix:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|M\right|=R\left|\Lambda\right|R^{-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Using these definitions, the interface terms arising in the FV formula have
 the following form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\mathcal{D}}\left(\boldsymbol{q^{-}},\boldsymbol{q^{+}}\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left(\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{q^{-}}\right)+\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{q^{+}}\right)+\hat{B}\cdot\left(\boldsymbol{q^{+}}-\boldsymbol{q^{-}}\right)-\hat{M}\cdot\left(\boldsymbol{q^{+}}-\boldsymbol{q^{-}}\right)\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}$
\end_inset

 is chosen to either correspond to a Rusanov/Lax-Friedrichs flux 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Toro2009"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{M}=\max\left(\max\left|\Lambda\left(\boldsymbol{q^{-}}\right)\right|,\max\left|\Lambda\left(\boldsymbol{q^{+}}\right)\right|\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or a simplified Osher–Solomon flux 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Dumbser2011,Dumbser2011a"

\end_inset

:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{M}=\int_{0}^{1}\left|M\left(\boldsymbol{\boldsymbol{q^{-}}}+z\left(\boldsymbol{q^{+}}-\boldsymbol{q^{-}}\right)\right)\right|dz
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}$
\end_inset

 takes the following form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\hat{B}=\int_{0}^{1}B\left(\boldsymbol{q^{-}}+z\left(\boldsymbol{q^{+}}-\boldsymbol{q}^{-}\right)\right)dz
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It was found that the Osher-Solomon flux would often produce slightly less
 diffusive results, but that it was more computationally expensive, and
