\begin_layout Paragraph
The Temperature Fix
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the original GFM, the entropy in the ghost region is fixed to the value
 of the interface cell in the real region (or, in the case of the isobaric
 fix, the second cell away from the interface).
 This was found to be inadequate in problems in which heat conduction across
 the material interface was desired, as the temperature in the ghost region
 then takes on an unrealistic value.
 Thus, when modeling problems involving intermaterial heat conduction with
 the GPR-RGFM, the density in the ghost region was fixed by a temperature
 requirement, rather than an entropy requirement.
 If the temperatures of materials 1 and 2 were 
\begin_inset Formula $T_{1},T_{2}$
\end_inset

 at the interface, the temperature in both of their ghost regions was set
 to 
\begin_inset Formula $T^{ghost}=\frac{T_{1}+T_{2}}{2}$
\end_inset

; a simple, intuitive choice to make.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $p^{ghost}=p^{*}$
\end_inset

.
 Thus, when using a stiffened gas EOS, the ghost density for both fluids
 is:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\rho^{ghost}=\frac{p^{*}+p_{\infty}}{\left(\gamma-1\right)c_{v}T^{ghost}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Let 
\begin_inset Formula $K=L$
\end_inset

 or 
\begin_inset Formula $K=R$
\end_inset

.
 To ensure condition 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DeterminantCondition"

\end_inset

 is satisfied, the following transformation is required:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
A_{K}^{*}\rightarrow\left(\frac{\rho^{ghost}}{\rho_{K}^{*}}\right)^{\frac{1}{3}}A_{K}^{*}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To ensure that 
\begin_inset Formula $q_{1}^{ghost}=q_{1}^{*}$
\end_inset

 after the temperature fix, the following transformation is required:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
J_{K}^{*}\rightarrow\frac{T_{K}^{*}}{T^{ghost}}J_{K}^{*}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
Numerical Results
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The GPR-RGFM is now assessed.
 The first three tests in this chapter are standard Riemann problems, exact
 solutions to which exist for the Euler equations.
 The viscosity of the GPR model smears the solutions in areas in which the
 solutions to the Euler equations are discontinuous or not smooth.
 This smearing is not the result of using a low-order solver (all results
 in these sections being calculated to third order).
 The last two tests assess the ability of the GPR-RGFM to correctly model
 heat conduction across interfaces, using the temperature fix described
 in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:An HPR Riemann Ghost Fluid Method"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Paragraph
Viscous Sod Shock Tube
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "sec:Viscous Sod Shock Tube"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The purpose of this test is to ensure that the GPR-RGFM can maintain a sharp
 contact discontinuity in the famous shock tube test of Sod 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Sod1978"

\end_inset

.
 A viscous ideal gas is used with 
\begin_inset Formula $\gamma=1.4$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\mu=5\times10^{-4}$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $P_{r}=2/3$
\end_inset

, as in Ren et al.
 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ren2014"

\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{v}=2.5$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $\rho_{0}=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $p_{0}=1$
\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset Formula $c_{s}=1$
\end_inset

, and 
\begin_inset Formula $\alpha=1$
\end_inset

.
 The initial conditions are given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "tab:SodShock"

\end_inset

.
 The final time is 
\begin_inset Formula $t=0.2$
\end_inset

 and all simulations used 200 cells.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The results in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "fig:Sod-Shock-Test"

\end_inset

 without the GPR-RGFM match those in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Ren2014"

\end_inset

 well.
 The viscous smearing in the density and the 
\begin_inset Quotes eld
\end_inset

bump
\begin_inset Quotes erd
\end_inset

 in the velocity at the contact discontinuity are present, as investigated
 by Jameson 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Jameson2008"

\end_inset

.
 When applying the GPR-RGFM, the contact discontinuity is now maintained,
 as it should be, as the gases are assumed to be immiscible.
 Additionally, the bump in the velocity is no longer present.
 This is correct, as the bump corresponds to a smearing of the density across
 the contact discontinuity, which should not occur for immiscible gases.
\end_layout

