\begin_layout Subsection
New Numerical Methods: Operator Splitting
\begin_inset CommandInset label
LatexCommand label
name "subsec:New-Numerical-Methods"

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DensityEquation"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:MomentumEquation"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:DistortionEquation"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ThermalEquation"

\end_inset

, 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:EnergyEquation"

\end_inset

 can be written in the following form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{Q}}{\partial t}+\boldsymbol{\nabla}\cdot\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)+\boldsymbol{B}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)\cdot\nabla\boldsymbol{Q}=\boldsymbol{S}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
As described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Toro2009"

\end_inset

, a viable way to solve inhomogeneous systems of PDEs is to employ an operator
 splitting.
 That is, the following subsystems are solved:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{Q}}{\partial t}+\boldsymbol{\nabla}\cdot\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)+\boldsymbol{B}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)\cdot\nabla\boldsymbol{Q} & =\boldsymbol{0}\label{eq:HomogeneousSubsystem}\\
\frac{d\boldsymbol{Q}}{dt} & =\boldsymbol{S}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)\label{eq:ODESubsystem}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
The advantage of this approach is that specialized solvers can be employed
 to compute the results of the different subsystems.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $H^{\delta t},S^{\delta t}$
\end_inset

 be the operators that take data 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q}\left(x,t\right)$
\end_inset

 to 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q}\left(x,t+\delta t\right)$
\end_inset

 under systems 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:HomogeneousSubsystem"

\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:ODESubsystem"

\end_inset

 respectively.
 A second-order scheme (in time) for solving the full set of PDEs over time
 step 
\begin_inset Formula $\left[0,\Delta t\right]$
\end_inset

 is obtained by calculating 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q_{\Delta t}}$
\end_inset

 using a Strang splitting:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{Q_{\Delta t}}=S^{\frac{\Delta t}{2}}H^{\Delta t}S^{\frac{\Delta t}{2}}\boldsymbol{Q_{0}}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
In the scheme proposed here, the homogeneous subsystem will be solved using
 a WENO reconstruction of the data, followed by a finite volume update,
 and the temporal ODEs will be solved with appropriate ODE solvers.
 This new scheme will be referred to here as 
\shape italic
the Split-WENO method
\shape default
.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Homogeneous System
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
A WENO reconstruction of the cell-averaged data is performed at the start
 of the time step (as described in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:The-ADER-WENO-Method"

\end_inset

).
 Focusing on a single cell 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset

 at time 
\begin_inset Formula $t_{n}$
\end_inset

, we have 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{w^{n}}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)=\boldsymbol{w^{n}}_{p}\Psi_{p}\left(\boldsymbol{\chi}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

 in 
\begin_inset Formula $C_{i}$
\end_inset

 where 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{p}$
\end_inset

 is a tensor product of basis functions in each of the spatial dimensions.
 The flux in 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 is approximated by 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)\approx\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{w}_{p}\right)\Psi_{p}\left(\boldsymbol{\chi}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)\right)$
\end_inset

.
 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{w}_{p}$
\end_inset

 are stepped forwards half a time step using the update formula:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\boldsymbol{w_{p}^{n+\frac{1}{2}}}-\boldsymbol{w_{p}^{n}}}{\Delta t/2}+\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{w_{k}^{n}}\right)\cdot\nabla\Psi_{k}\left(\boldsymbol{\chi_{p}}\right)+\boldsymbol{B}\left(\boldsymbol{w_{p}^{n}}\right)\cdot\left(\boldsymbol{w_{k}^{n}}\nabla\Psi_{k}\left(\boldsymbol{\chi_{p}}\right)\right)=\boldsymbol{0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
i.e.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{w_{p}^{n+\frac{1}{2}}}=\boldsymbol{w_{p}^{n}}-\frac{\Delta t}{2\Delta x}\left(\boldsymbol{F}\left(\boldsymbol{w_{k}^{n}}\right)\cdot\nabla\Psi_{k}\left(\boldsymbol{\chi_{p}}\right)+\boldsymbol{B}\left(\boldsymbol{w_{p}^{n}}\right)\cdot\left(\boldsymbol{w_{k}^{n}}\nabla\Psi_{k}\left(\boldsymbol{\chi_{p}}\right)\right)\right)\label{eq:WENO half step}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\chi_{p}}$
\end_inset

 is the node corresponding to 
\begin_inset Formula $\Psi_{p}$
\end_inset

.
 This evolution to the middle of the time step is similar to that used in
 the second-order MUSCL and SLIC schemes (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Toro2009"

\end_inset

) and, as with those schemes, it is integral to giving the method presented
 here its second-order accuracy.
 
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Integrating 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:HomogeneousSubsystem"

\end_inset

 over 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 gives:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{Q_{i}^{n+1}}=\boldsymbol{Q_{i}^{n}}-\Delta t_{n}\left(\boldsymbol{P_{i}^{n+\frac{1}{2}}}+\boldsymbol{D_{i}^{n+\frac{1}{2}}}\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\boldsymbol{Q_{i}^{n}} & =\frac{1}{V}\int_{C}\boldsymbol{Q}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t_{n}\right)d\boldsymbol{x}\\
\boldsymbol{P_{i}^{n+\frac{1}{2}}} & =\frac{1}{V}\int_{C}\boldsymbol{B}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t_{n+\frac{1}{2}}\right)\right)\cdot\nabla\boldsymbol{Q}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t_{n+\frac{1}{2}}\right)d\boldsymbol{x}\\
\boldsymbol{D_{i}^{n+\frac{1}{2}}} & =\frac{1}{V}\varoint_{\partial C}\boldsymbol{\mathcal{D}}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}\left(\boldsymbol{s},t_{n+\frac{1}{2}}\right),\boldsymbol{Q^{+}}\left(\boldsymbol{s},t_{n+\frac{1}{2}}\right)\right)d\boldsymbol{s}
\end{align}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
end{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $V$
\end_inset

 is the volume of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q^{-},Q^{+}}$
\end_inset

 are the interior and exterior extrapolated states at the boundary of 
\begin_inset Formula $C$
\end_inset

, respectively.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Note that 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand eqref
reference "eq:HomogeneousSubsystem"

\end_inset

 can be rewritten as:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{Q}}{\partial t}+\boldsymbol{M}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\right)\cdot\nabla\boldsymbol{Q}=\boldsymbol{0}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{M}=\frac{\partial\boldsymbol{F}}{\partial\boldsymbol{Q}}+\boldsymbol{B}$
\end_inset

.
 Let 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{n}$
\end_inset

 be the normal to the boundary at point 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{s}\in\partial C$
\end_inset

.
 For the GPR model, 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}=\boldsymbol{M}\left(\boldsymbol{Q}\left(\boldsymbol{s}\right)\right)\cdot\boldsymbol{n}$
\end_inset

 is a diagonalizable matrix with decomposition 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{M}=\hat{R}\hat{\Lambda}\hat{R}^{-1}$
\end_inset

 where the columns of 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{R}$
\end_inset

 are the right eigenvectors and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{\Lambda}$
\end_inset

 is the diagonal matrix of eigenvalues.
 Define also 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{\hat{F}}=\boldsymbol{F}\cdot\boldsymbol{n}$
\end_inset

 and 
\begin_inset Formula $\hat{B}=\boldsymbol{B}\cdot\boldsymbol{n}$
\end_inset

.
 Using these definitions, the interface terms arising in the FV formula
 have the following form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\boldsymbol{\mathcal{D}}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{-}},\boldsymbol{Q^{+}}\right)=\frac{1}{2}\left(\boldsymbol{\hat{F}}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{+}}\right)+\boldsymbol{\hat{F}}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}\right)+\tilde{B}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{+}}-\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}\right)+\tilde{M}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{+}}-\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}\right)\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{M}$
\end_inset

 is chosen to either correspond to a Rusanov/Lax-Friedrichs flux (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Toro2009"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{M}=\max\left(\max\left|\hat{\Lambda}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{+}}\right)\right|,\max\left|\hat{\Lambda}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}\right)\right|\right)
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
or a simplified Osher–Solomon flux (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand citet
key "Dumbser2011a,Dumbser2011b"

\end_inset

):
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{M}=\int_{0}^{1}\left|\hat{M}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}+z\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{+}}-\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}\right)\right)\right|dz
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
where
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\left|\hat{M}\right|=\hat{R}\left|\hat{\Lambda}\right|\hat{R}^{-1}
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\tilde{B}$
\end_inset

 takes the following form:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{equation}
\tilde{B}=\int_{0}^{1}\hat{B}\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}+z\left(\boldsymbol{Q^{+}}-\boldsymbol{Q^{-}}\right)\right)dz
\end{equation}

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
It was found that the Osher-Solomon flux would often produce slightly less
 diffusive results, but that it was more computationally expensive, and
 also had a greater tendency to introduce numerical artefacts.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{P_{i}^{n+\frac{1}{2}}},\boldsymbol{D_{i}^{n+\frac{1}{2}}}$
\end_inset

 are calculated using an 
\begin_inset Formula $N+1$
\end_inset

-point Gauss-Legendre quadrature, replacing 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{Q}\left(\boldsymbol{x},t_{n+\frac{1}{2}}\right)$
\end_inset

 with 
\begin_inset Formula $\boldsymbol{w^{n+\frac{1}{2}}}\left(\boldsymbol{x}\right)$
\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Subsubsection
The Temporal ODEs
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Noting that 
\begin_inset Formula $\frac{d\rho}{dt}=0$
\end_inset

 over the ODE time step, the operator 
\begin_inset Formula $S$
\end_inset

 entails solving the following systems:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset ERT
status open

\begin_layout Plain Layout


\backslash
begin{subequations}
\end_layout

\end_inset


\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
\begin_inset Formula 
\begin{align}
\frac{dA}{dt} & =\frac{-3}{\tau_{1}}\left|A\right|^{\frac{5}{3}}A\dev\left(G\right)\label{eq:DistortionODE}\\
\frac{d\boldsymbol{J}}{dt} & =-\frac{1}{\tau_{2}}\frac{T\rho_{0}}{T_{0}\rho}\boldsymbol{J}\label{eq:ThermalODE}
\end{align}

