\begin_layout Section
Outline for Future Work
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To restate the research objectives given in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "sec:Research-Objectives"

\end_inset

, my PhD project consists of the following components:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
To develop stable and accurate techniques to deal with the interfaces between
 different materials in multimaterial / multiphase problems
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
To combine the GPR model with the models we use to describe the reactions
 of a combustible materials
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
To develop numerical methods for solving the GPR model in a reasonable amount
 of time
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
To address each of these objectives one-by-one:
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
As was seen in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:Simulating-Material-Interfaces"

\end_inset

, I have developed a stable numerical method for dealing with material interface
s under the GPR model.
 This has only been tested in one dimension, however.
 It is well-know that in multiple dimensions issues with accuracy and stability
 can arise in ghost fluid methods and their accompanying methods of evolution
 of the position the interface (in this study, level set methods) 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Desjardins2008,Terashima2009"

\end_inset

.
 This extension to multiple dimensions and consequent analysis remains to
 be done for the ghost fluid method I have developed, and I will also be
 comparing it with the more recent cut-cell methods (see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Berger,Methods2011"

\end_inset

 for an overview), as they have been demonstrated to outperform ghost fluid
 methods in some situations.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
Although I have combined the GPR model with simple Arrhenius reaction kinetics
 terms, as seen in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:Combining-the-GPR"

\end_inset

, there remains a great deal of work to incorporate more complicated reaction
 pathways (for example, see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Romenski2010"

\end_inset

), and extra terms to keep track of the state information of both reactants
 and products (e.g.
 see 
\begin_inset CommandInset citation
LatexCommand cite
key "Michael2016"

\end_inset

).
 Although this should be straightforward, there may be unforseen difficulties
 in accomplishing this with the GPR model, and in any case this work will
 be time-consuming.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Enumerate
As seen in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:New-Numerical-Methods"

\end_inset

, I have developed a new numerical method for the GPR model that is significantl
y faster than the currently-available ADER-WENO methods (achieving over
 an order-of-magnitude speed-up on stiff test cases), but still able to
 attain second-order accurate solutions.
 The theoretical work I have presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:New-Numerical-Methods2"

\end_inset

 to improve further upon this method needs to be validated with further
 test cases, and I will perform this for the test cases presented in 
\begin_inset CommandInset ref
LatexCommand formatted
reference "subsec:New-Numerical-Methods"

\end_inset

.
\end_layout

\begin_layout Standard
Except in the case of unforseen difficulties in any of these noted extensions
 to the work I have already performed, it is reasonable to expect that I
 will be able to complete these tasks over the course of my second year,
 given the pace of my research output in my first year.
